[Music] Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger In today's&nbsp;
video, we are going to move towards understanding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:15.720 --> 00:00:24.640
abstract algebra, a large and lovely area of&nbsp;
mathematics with lots of applications, especially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.640 --> 00:00:31.120
20th-century developments. We're going to look&nbsp;
at laying the foundations for this subject in,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:31.120 --> 00:00:43.840
of course, a better, more solid, more tangible,&nbsp;
and computable way than we currently have.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:48.960
We're going to be relying very much on our data&nbsp;
structure point of view and the lessons that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:57.440
have learned about just how to set up fundamental&nbsp;
arithmetic and a little bit of maxels and vexels.

00:00:57.440 --> 00:01:04.160
Okay, so what is abstract algebra? Well, it's not&nbsp;
that easy to say. It's a kind of an extension of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:04.160 --> 00:01:12.680
arithmetic or algebra to more general situations,&nbsp;
and these general situations include lots of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:19.840
things which have perhaps some fancy names.&nbsp;
So we're talking about groups, rings, fields,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:29.240
vector spaces, algebras, lattices, modules,&nbsp;
Lie algebras, hypergroups, and one could fill&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:29.240 --> 00:01:36.760
the page with more objects that are studied&nbsp;
in modern abstract algebra. Roughly speaking,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:43.800
this list sort of corresponds to the order&nbsp;
in which an undergraduate might learn about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:50.120
these various topics, but there's&nbsp;
quite a bit of variability possible.

00:01:50.120 --> 00:01:56.680
Okay, so the common features of most of&nbsp;
these situations are that we have some basic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:56.680 --> 00:02:04.440
algebraic objects, usually one or two algebraic&nbsp;
objects, and they're often called addition or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:11.880
multiplication or variants of them, but not&nbsp;
always. Another common feature is that we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:19.520
generally generalizing common or familiar objects&nbsp;
or arithmetical situations. So the idea is that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:19.520 --> 00:02:27.080
we have some particular domain of investigation&nbsp;
in which we have some arithmetical operations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:35.720
and we look at the essential features of that&nbsp;
situation and try to extract the skeletal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:42.440
underpinnings of that situation in order to&nbsp;
generalize. So we start with a particular object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.440 --> 00:02:48.680
and then we want to generalize to include a&nbsp;
wider family of objects that share a lot of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:48.680 --> 00:02:54.160
the properties of the main one that we&nbsp;
started with. And the idea is then to,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:54.160 --> 00:03:00.440
well, try to say things in a way that&nbsp;
covers this wider range of objects,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:06.760
even though maybe we're still focusing&nbsp;
our intuition on the fundamental examples.

00:03:06.760 --> 00:03:11.640
Okay, so what do we do in abstract algebra?&nbsp;
Well, one of the kinds of things that we do is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:11.640 --> 00:03:19.080
we are interested in structure. We're interested&nbsp;
in determining what these objects look like,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.080 --> 00:03:30.920
and we're interested in classifying them to create&nbsp;
lists or a taxonomy of various things that satisfy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:30.920 --> 00:03:38.200
the framework that we have generalized. And once&nbsp;
we start doing abstract algebra quite a lot,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:38.200 --> 00:03:46.040
we start to see that there are certain patterns of&nbsp;
thinking, certain standard kinds of constructions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.040 --> 00:03:52.840
or ideas that end up recurring, including, for&nbsp;
example, the idea of substructure. We identify&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:52.840 --> 00:03:57.480
some particular kind of structure, and then we&nbsp;
look inside those structures for other structures&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:57.480 --> 00:04:06.560
that are basically similar to the original one.&nbsp;
We think about product or sum structures. We've&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:10.040
got some kind of object, maybe a group, and&nbsp;
over here is another group. We think about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:10.040 --> 00:04:17.480
how we can combine those groups, maybe add them&nbsp;
or multiply them to create some bigger group. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:23.720
look at quotient structures—that's a little bit&nbsp;
more subtle. So that's what happens when you have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:30.840
one object of a certain kind, and then inside you&nbsp;
have some other kind of object of the same kind,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:34.600
but it's definitely inside. And then&nbsp;
the idea of sort of taking a quotient,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:34.600 --> 00:04:40.640
like dividing the big one by the little one, to&nbsp;
get another, a third kind of object of the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:40.640 --> 00:04:46.920
kind. So investigating when that's possible,&nbsp;
that's an interesting kind of question.

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:52.200
A very general kind of consideration is&nbsp;
the idea of understanding relationships&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:57.600
between two objects, like let's say we're&nbsp;
looking at lattices. So here's a lattice,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.600 --> 00:05:04.200
there's a lattice. We're interested in what kind&nbsp;
of relations there are between these lattices,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.200 --> 00:05:10.000
and this is often framed in terms of the&nbsp;
word homomorphism, which we think of as a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:17.800
mapping or a function or a transformation that&nbsp;
takes the elements of one lattice to the other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:17.800 --> 00:05:25.400
lattice but preserves the lattice properties. So&nbsp;
whatever a lattice is, it has certain properties,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:25.400 --> 00:05:34.040
and we want our relations and homomorphisms to&nbsp;
preserve or to respect the various arithmetical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:34.040 --> 00:05:41.480
or algebraic structures that we have. So&nbsp;
these are some of the common features that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:41.480 --> 00:05:49.600
figure in pretty well the study of any one of&nbsp;
these kinds of abstract algebraic structures.

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:58.240
So today, we want to give a very brief kind of&nbsp;
overview of some of these kinds of objects in a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:58.240 --> 00:06:05.200
kind of cursory overview but with a traditional&nbsp;
point of view. All right, so this is following&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:13.280
sort of standard thinking, and then later on, we&nbsp;
want to move towards a better, new, improved way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:13.280 --> 00:06:19.760
of thinking about these same things. But let's&nbsp;
start with a somewhat more familiar look at them.

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:26.120
Now, it's often considered that group theory&nbsp;
is the natural entrance to abstract algebra&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:26.120 --> 00:06:31.960
because it's an algebraic situation where you&nbsp;
only have one operation, and the operation is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.960 --> 00:06:37.840
sometimes called addition and sometimes called&nbsp;
multiplication. So I'm not going to, in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:37.840 --> 00:06:43.600
lecture, concentrate on the official definitions&nbsp;
of things. I'm going to rather give you a brief&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:49.080
orientation by showing you some examples. Now,&nbsp;
we actually have talked about groups a number of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:54.200
times already in this series. You can have a look&nbsp;
through the series for some examples, for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:54.200 --> 00:07:01.000
when we were talking about the projective line,&nbsp;
projective plane, and isometries. So say the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:08.200
projective line, okay? So another example of a&nbsp;
group that we've talked about is these U-groups.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:18.560
So for example, U10, and U10 was the integers less&nbsp;
than 10 that are relatively prime to 10. In other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:23.480
words, integers that don't have any factors&nbsp;
in common with 10. So that would be 1, 3, 7,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:31.880
and 9. And we saw that we could make an algebraic&nbsp;
structure out of just those four objects by doing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:39.160
multiplication mod 10. All right, so here's the&nbsp;
multiplication table that we considered. One is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:47.480
the identity, so 1 * anything is that anything,&nbsp;
and say 3 * 7. Well, that's 21, but if we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:47.480 --> 00:07:56.760
working mod 10, 21 is the same as 1, so 3 * 7 is&nbsp;
1. And this is a commutative group, reflected in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.760 --> 00:08:04.160
the symmetry of the multiplication table, that&nbsp;
the 9 * 3 entry is the same as the 3 * 9 entry, so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.160 --> 00:08:12.240
that entry and that entry are the same. And that's&nbsp;
a very special and pleasant kind of group. It's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:12.240 --> 00:08:18.480
much simpler than the non-commutative groups, and&nbsp;
so the basic properties of a group are that the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:18.480 --> 00:08:24.280
multiplication should be associative, that there&nbsp;
should be an identity element (in this case, one),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:24.280 --> 00:08:29.680
and that every element should have an inverse.&nbsp;
Basically, it means that along every row or every&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:29.680 --> 00:08:37.520
column, you can find a one entry. So those are&nbsp;
commutative groups, and they are quite a pleasant&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:44.520
thing to study, and they come up in practice, for&nbsp;
example, here, okay? But in other situations too.

00:08:44.520 --> 00:08:50.760
And then there are non-commutative groups, which&nbsp;
have the same underlying rules, except that the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:55.800
multiplication of two elements doesn't need to be&nbsp;
commutative. So a * b does not have to be equal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.800 --> 00:09:03.040
to b * a. And we've seen some examples of that,&nbsp;
for example, the group S3, which is the group of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.040 --> 00:09:15.480
permutations of three things. We can label those&nbsp;
by thinking about the ordered sets which have 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:15.480 --> 00:09:21.560
2, and 3 as their elements. So these are like&nbsp;
ordered sets or permutations. These are the six&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:21.560 --> 00:09:30.520
possible ways of rearranging three objects,&nbsp;
and one interpretation of this group S3—it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:30.520 --> 00:09:37.240
the symmetric group on three things—is as the&nbsp;
transformations of a triangle. So if we here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:43.160
have a triangle with positions 1, 2, and 3, then,&nbsp;
for example, we can think about the transformation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:43.160 --> 00:09:51.240
that takes this triangle and rotates it by a third&nbsp;
of a turn in this direction. Okay, so we take&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:51.240 --> 00:09:59.280
this triangle here to this position here. Let's&nbsp;
call that transformation sigma, okay? Then that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:07.840
transformation can be recorded. One way is to say,&nbsp;
well, the one object goes to the two position,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:07.840 --> 00:10:13.040
the two object goes to the three position, and&nbsp;
the three object goes to the one position. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:13.040 --> 00:10:18.080
we could record that by having a little table like&nbsp;
this: here are the initial objects, and here are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:23.000
the new positions that they go to. So the object&nbsp;
one goes to the position two, the object two goes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:27.600
to the position three, the object three goes to&nbsp;
the position one. And once we have a little table&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:27.600 --> 00:10:33.520
like that, we can also say, well, why don't we&nbsp;
just record the last row, the bottom row, because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:39.320
the first row is always 1, 2, 3, and so we can&nbsp;
associate this thing with the ordered set 2, 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:45.920
1. So that would be one way of identifying these&nbsp;
permutations or transformations of a triangle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:45.920 --> 00:10:54.120
with these ordered sets. And in this context, the&nbsp;
multiplication is that of combining or composing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:54.120 --> 00:10:59.280
transformations. So you do one transformation, and&nbsp;
then you do another transformation after that one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:04.760
and that's called composing the transformations,&nbsp;
and that gives an algebraic structure to our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:04.760 --> 00:11:12.240
permutations. That's a non-commutative group.&nbsp;
So that's a very interesting family of algebraic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:12.240 --> 00:11:19.240
objects—very beautiful, very rich theory. The&nbsp;
non-commutative situation is typically a lot more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:19.240 --> 00:11:25.680
advanced and richer and more complicated than&nbsp;
the commutative theory. This division between&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:31.440
commutative and non-commutative kinds of abstract&nbsp;
algebra is a central one in the subject in terms&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:38.240
of organizing the subject. And that also holds&nbsp;
with our next example, the example of rings.

00:11:38.240 --> 00:11:43.200
Okay, so let's start with an example of a&nbsp;
commutative ring, and there's a very familiar&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:50.840
example: the example of integers or int. So now we&nbsp;
have two operations: addition and multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:50.840 --> 00:11:57.120
and it's a question of studying not just those&nbsp;
operations in themselves but also how they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:57.120 --> 00:12:04.560
interact. So, for example, the addition operation&nbsp;
is commutative and associative, and also the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:04.560 --> 00:12:12.880
multiplication is commutative and associative.&nbsp;
It's the multiplication being commutative that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:12.880 --> 00:12:19.800
makes the ring be called commutative. The&nbsp;
addition always has to be commutative. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:19.800 --> 00:12:25.200
in addition, the two operations interact via&nbsp;
the distributive law that's very familiar to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:34.640
us. And there's also some extra kinds of things.&nbsp;
There's a zero element which plays an identity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:34.640 --> 00:12:39.760
element in terms of addition. There's a one&nbsp;
element which plays an identity role in terms&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:39.760 --> 00:12:46.680
of multiplication. And then there's a notion of&nbsp;
inverse, closely related to the minus one object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:46.680 --> 00:12:54.120
that allows us to start with an element six and&nbsp;
obtain the inverse of six, namely such that when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:54.120 --> 00:12:59.880
we add them, we get the additive identity.&nbsp;
So that's an example of a commutative ring.

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:04.360
And generally, we like to have more than one&nbsp;
example of an algebraic structure. If we don't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:04.360 --> 00:13:10.080
have more than one example, then it's not really&nbsp;
important enough to think about generalizing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:10.080 --> 00:13:14.800
So we want to have something where we have a&nbsp;
couple of different situations that all have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:18.760
some common features, and we can say, ah,&nbsp;
there's some common things going on here in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:18.760 --> 00:13:27.440
these different situations; let's abstract those&nbsp;
common features and study this thing abstractly.

00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:32.920
Okay, so aside from the integers, another&nbsp;
important commutative ring is the ring&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:32.920 --> 00:13:40.880
of polynomials or, for us, poly numbers,&nbsp;
which we might denote by poly int. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:40.880 --> 00:13:48.240
so we're talking about things that look like&nbsp;
this in the poly number language. So we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:48.240 --> 00:13:54.360
combinations of numbers, alphas, alpha squares,&nbsp;
alpha cubes, and so on. These are familiar ways&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:54.360 --> 00:14:00.600
of writing things down which actually officially&nbsp;
are more like column vectors. And we know that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:00.600 --> 00:14:09.480
can add two such polynomials or poly numbers&nbsp;
basically pointwise, so 2 and 3 give us 5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:09.480 --> 00:14:14.360
the alpha minus 4 alpha give us minus 3 alpha,&nbsp;
and the alpha squared was there. But we can also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:14.360 --> 00:14:19.640
multiply them in the kind of distributed&nbsp;
way so that 2 minus alpha times 1 plus 4&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:19.640 --> 00:14:25.320
alpha would be 2 and then plus 8 alpha&nbsp;
minus alpha is a total of 7 alpha,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:25.320 --> 00:14:31.120
and minus 4 alpha squared. And with these two&nbsp;
operations of addition and multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:36.320
we get a situation which is very parallel&nbsp;
to that of the integers. It's a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:43.360
bigger and more broad, but it shares a lot of&nbsp;
essential features. And so you can think about a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:43.360 --> 00:14:49.880
commutative ring as being some kind of attempt at&nbsp;
generalizing what goes on in these two examples.

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:57.560
So after commutative rings, there's some case&nbsp;
to be made that a field is a natural next kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:57.560 --> 00:15:05.000
of abstract algebraic object to consider. So&nbsp;
the main example there is the rational numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:11.720
okay? And that's an algebraic domain where we&nbsp;
have addition and multiplication, but prominently,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:11.720 --> 00:15:17.320
we also have the inverses of those. We&nbsp;
have subtraction, which we also have in a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:17.320 --> 00:15:23.920
commutative ring, but what's especially important&nbsp;
is that we have division at least almost all the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:23.920 --> 00:15:32.200
time. So a field is a commutative ring with,&nbsp;
in addition, the possibility of division by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:32.200 --> 00:15:41.480
nonzero numbers. So we want that every nonzero&nbsp;
number has an inverse, a multiplicative inverse,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:41.480 --> 00:15:46.760
just corresponding to the fact that if you take&nbsp;
a rational number like 5/7, then its inverse&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:46.760 --> 00:15:55.040
is 7/5. So the rational numbers are a very&nbsp;
interesting and important algebraic domain,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:55.040 --> 00:16:01.920
but also full of some subtlety. In particular,&nbsp;
there is the key ambiguity in the specification&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:01.920 --> 00:16:08.720
of rational numbers because we know that rational&nbsp;
numbers are not uniquely defined. 2/3 is the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:08.720 --> 00:16:17.440
as 8/12, the same as -14/-21, and the rule, of&nbsp;
course, is that there's an unambiguous way of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:23.320
deciding whether two things are equal. So we would&nbsp;
check this by checking that 2 * 12 is the same as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:23.320 --> 00:16:32.520
3 * 8. Okay, but that does make the analysis and&nbsp;
study of rational numbers definitely a little&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:41.320
bit trickier because you have to factor in this&nbsp;
ambiguity in how you specify one of the objects.

00:16:41.320 --> 00:16:45.680
And then, for example, we have addition in&nbsp;
a kind of a familiar way that we all know.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:45.680 --> 00:16:50.920
We have multiplication, which is familiar enough.&nbsp;
We have division, where you basically multiply by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:50.920 --> 00:16:58.480
the inverse or the reciprocal. And so these are&nbsp;
standard examples, but it's a very rich field,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:58.480 --> 00:17:04.880
a very important field. Now, students of abstract&nbsp;
algebra these days learn immediately that there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:04.880 --> 00:17:10.520
are then other fields as well. There are fields&nbsp;
like the real numbers and the complex numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:10.520 --> 00:17:17.920
and maybe fields like a + bθ, where a and b are&nbsp;
rational numbers. This is highly unfortunate,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:24.840
okay? It's highly unfortunate when students of&nbsp;
abstract algebra, after having spent some time&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:24.840 --> 00:17:30.880
thinking about rational numbers, are quickly&nbsp;
indoctrinated to believe that there are then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:36.320
these other fields R and C that are pretty&nbsp;
well the same as rational numbers. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:36.320 --> 00:17:43.840
this is a huge misunderstanding and a blind&nbsp;
spot in modern mathematics. Okay, so in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:43.840 --> 00:17:50.440
going from rational numbers to R and C is a huge&nbsp;
step in complexity that really takes us outside of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:57.120
abstract algebra. Okay, the essence of the idea&nbsp;
of these two things, which is already faulty,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:57.120 --> 00:18:02.880
but the essence of this faulty idea is that&nbsp;
we can start doing arithmetic with infinite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:02.880 --> 00:18:11.000
processes. Okay, that's the whole point—that&nbsp;
we can take an infinite number of additions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:16.880
we can take an infinite number of multiplications,&nbsp;
and we can output the results of those infinite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:16.880 --> 00:18:25.880
kinds of procedures and have a viable arithmetic.&nbsp;
But modern students are not told the subtleties,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:25.880 --> 00:18:30.440
and so they're just, you know, taught that, well,&nbsp;
there's the rational numbers, and there's the real&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:30.440 --> 00:18:34.520
numbers and the complex numbers, and they're&nbsp;
all pretty well the same. But the reality is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:34.520 --> 00:18:40.320
that they're dramatically different. This&nbsp;
is much, much more solid. These things are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:46.760
fraught with difficulties, and in fact, when you&nbsp;
look carefully, they don't really work. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:46.760 --> 00:18:53.840
so we have a very big difference of opinion when&nbsp;
it comes to field theory, and that's going to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:53.840 --> 00:18:59.120
a big point here—that our field theory is going&nbsp;
to be very different from the field theory that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:59.120 --> 00:19:06.520
you learn at universities these days. We're&nbsp;
going to do field theory solidly, correctly.

00:19:06.520 --> 00:19:11.200
So then there's non-commutative rings.&nbsp;
So we started with commutative rings and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:11.200 --> 00:19:16.840
then fields, and now we can sort of&nbsp;
backtrack to non-commutative rings,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:16.840 --> 00:19:26.280
where the addition is still commutative, but the&nbsp;
multiplication now is no longer commutative. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:26.280 --> 00:19:31.760
there's a standard example of this, which is&nbsp;
a very rich example and hugely important in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:39.360
mathematics—the example of matrices. And the&nbsp;
simple example is already very interesting:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:39.360 --> 00:19:46.200
the 2x2 matrices with integer entries. This is an&nbsp;
arithmetical domain in which we have operations&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:46.200 --> 00:19:53.000
of addition and multiplication. So the addition&nbsp;
of 2x2 matrices is just the usual pointwise one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:59.920
and the product of 2x2 matrices—we know it's this&nbsp;
sort of funny multiplication where, to get this 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:59.920 --> 00:20:09.560
you multiply that row by that column, so 1&nbsp;
* 2 + 2 * 0. And this -1 is 1 * -7 + 2 * 3.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:09.560 --> 00:20:20.680
And that -2 is -1 * 2 + 4 * 0. And that&nbsp;
19 is -1 * -7 + 4 * 3. And in this arena,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:20.680 --> 00:20:27.360
we also have this distinguished zero element,&nbsp;
which is the identity for addition—just the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:27.360 --> 00:20:33.800
matrix of all zeros. And then we have this curious&nbsp;
identity element for multiplication called I,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:33.800 --> 00:20:39.800
which is this matrix with ones on the&nbsp;
diagonal and zeros off the diagonal. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:39.800 --> 00:20:44.800
and this whole story generalizes to 3x3&nbsp;
matrices, 4x4 matrices, and so on. And so we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:44.800 --> 00:20:51.160
have this family of these non-commutative rings.&nbsp;
They're very important in mathematics, generating&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:51.160 --> 00:20:58.520
all kinds of interesting arithmetic that goes&nbsp;
beyond the arithmetic that we're familiar with.

00:20:58.520 --> 00:21:03.520
And the last abstract algebraic structure that&nbsp;
I want to tell you about today is probably the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:03.520 --> 00:21:11.040
most common one, the one that undergraduates end&nbsp;
up using practically the most—the idea of a vector&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:11.040 --> 00:21:23.000
space over a field. Okay, there's a very common&nbsp;
example of this, which is the vectors in dimension&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:32.800
three, say, with rational number entries. So this&nbsp;
AB object is actually rather technically subtle to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:32.800 --> 00:21:37.800
set up because you need to understand what a field&nbsp;
is first. And we're going to talk about this.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:44.640
Let's say if we use the rational numbers, which is&nbsp;
our generic field, then we can think about vectors&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:44.640 --> 00:21:50.800
with three components whose entries are rational&nbsp;
numbers. Okay, and the operations here—there are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:50.800 --> 00:21:56.240
two operations, but they're not exactly what you&nbsp;
might think. The first one is vector addition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:56.240 --> 00:22:04.320
which is just the usual addition of vectors&nbsp;
component-wise, like here. But the multiplication&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:04.320 --> 00:22:09.760
is a more limited multiplication; it's not really&nbsp;
the same as in the ring story. It's not as if we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:09.760 --> 00:22:16.080
multiply two vectors; rather, the multiplication&nbsp;
here is what's called scalar multiplication. So in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:16.080 --> 00:22:24.080
a vector space, we have the idea of multiplying&nbsp;
vectors by elements in our field. All right,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:24.080 --> 00:22:28.920
so for example, here is a vector, and here is&nbsp;
a number five, which we think of as being an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:28.920 --> 00:22:35.360
element in the field. And five times this&nbsp;
vector—that makes sense, and it's just the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:35.360 --> 00:22:43.560
obvious pointwise multiplication of each entry&nbsp;
here by that scalar. And this is a very important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:43.560 --> 00:22:49.120
algebraic object because it's the algebraic&nbsp;
embodiment of our three-dimensional space,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:49.120 --> 00:22:55.000
right? We live in three-dimensional space, and&nbsp;
we like to describe that by having coordinates&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:55.000 --> 00:23:02.480
in a familiar kind of way, and then, you know,&nbsp;
labeling axes and then using parallel lines and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:02.480 --> 00:23:08.160
so on to specify directions. So, for example,&nbsp;
go two in this direction and three in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:08.160 --> 00:23:13.680
direction and four in this direction; then we&nbsp;
can get this combined transformation from zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:13.680 --> 00:23:24.040
up to here. So this red directed segment is the&nbsp;
vector (2, 3, 4). It gives us a very physical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:24.040 --> 00:23:29.320
interpretation of this algebraic structure.&nbsp;
And this is hugely important in engineering&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:29.320 --> 00:23:40.000
and many applications and really is a workhorse&nbsp;
for linear algebra, for setting up linear algebra.

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:45.960
There's another example of vector spaces over&nbsp;
fields. So, for example, we could take the 2x2&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:45.960 --> 00:23:51.600
matrices—in fact, we could take n by m matrices,&nbsp;
they don't have to be square—so just the space of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:51.600 --> 00:23:59.800
matrices of a fixed kind or a fixed shape with&nbsp;
rational number entries. You can add those,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:59.800 --> 00:24:05.920
and you can multiply them by scalars, and so that&nbsp;
naturally forms a vector space. But there are, in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:05.920 --> 00:24:13.000
fact, lots of different examples of vector spaces,&nbsp;
and this is a kind of a key abstract algebraic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:18.440
object that we're, in fact, going to start with.&nbsp;
So when we start looking at abstract algebra, this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:18.440 --> 00:24:25.440
is actually going to be the first one that we look&nbsp;
at seriously, and that'll be quite interesting.

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:31.640
But before we do that, I want to share with&nbsp;
you some of the challenges that modern abstract&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:31.640 --> 00:24:38.560
algebra has. Now, abstract algebra is not as&nbsp;
fraught with difficulties as modern analysis.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:38.560 --> 00:24:45.760
Modern analysis has very, very serious problems.&nbsp;
The problems with abstract algebra are also not to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:45.760 --> 00:24:51.880
be diminished; they are also reasonably serious,&nbsp;
but they're not as extensive as for analysis.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:51.880 --> 00:24:56.240
But nevertheless, we do have to acknowledge&nbsp;
what they are and have some understanding of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:56.240 --> 00:25:04.040
the challenges that we need to overcome to&nbsp;
set up abstract algebra properly, solidly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:04.040 --> 00:25:10.280
in the 21st century. And so the first thing&nbsp;
to understand there is what the problems are,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:10.280 --> 00:25:15.160
and then we can talk about how we're&nbsp;
going to overcome them and move beyond.

00:25:15.160 --> 00:25:17.680
All right, so that's what we're going to&nbsp;
do in our next video. We're going to look&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:17.680 --> 00:25:23.360
at some of the logical challenges&nbsp;
with modern abstract algebra. I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:23.360 --> 00:25:27.680
hope you'll join me for that. I'm Norman&nbsp;
Wildberger. Thanks for listening [Music].

